<DocsLayout title="Monitoring & Iteration" description="CloudWatch monitoring, diagnosing a production incident, and reflecting on your first cloud deployment.">
  <h1 class="mb-6">Monitoring & Iteration</h1>
  <p class="text-text-secondary mb-8">Jake signed off. UAT issues are fixed and deployed. Tidal Brewing is live. For the first time, you're responsible for the infrastructure it runs on — not just the application.</p>

  <h2 class="mb-4">CloudWatch metrics</h2>
  <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4">CloudWatch is AWS's built-in monitoring service. For an EC2-based deployment, these are the metrics that matter:</p>

  <div class="overflow-x-auto mb-6">
    <table class="w-full text-sm border-collapse">
      <thead>
        <tr class="bg-bg-muted">
          <th class="text-left px-4 py-3 font-semibold border-b border-border">Metric</th>
          <th class="text-left px-4 py-3 font-semibold border-b border-border">Normal range</th>
          <th class="text-left px-4 py-3 font-semibold border-b border-border">What it tells you</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr class="border-b border-border">
          <td class="px-4 py-3">CPU utilisation</td>
          <td class="px-4 py-3 text-text-secondary">Under 10%</td>
          <td class="px-4 py-3 text-text-secondary">How hard the instance is working. t2.micro has limited CPU credits — sustained high CPU means burst capacity is depleted.</td>
        </tr>
        <tr class="border-b border-border bg-bg-subtle">
          <td class="px-4 py-3">Memory usage</td>
          <td class="px-4 py-3 text-text-secondary">Under 70%</td>
          <td class="px-4 py-3 text-text-secondary">Requires CloudWatch agent (not available by default). t2.micro has 1 GB — Docker containers compete for memory. If PostgreSQL and the app are fighting, things get slow.</td>
        </tr>
        <tr class="border-b border-border">
          <td class="px-4 py-3">Disk usage</td>
          <td class="px-4 py-3 text-text-secondary">Under 60%</td>
          <td class="px-4 py-3 text-text-secondary">Also via CloudWatch agent. Docker images, database files, and logs accumulate. A full disk crashes everything silently.</td>
        </tr>
        <tr class="border-b border-border bg-bg-subtle">
          <td class="px-4 py-3">Network in/out</td>
          <td class="px-4 py-3 text-text-secondary">Variable</td>
          <td class="px-4 py-3 text-text-secondary">Traffic volume. Useful for spotting traffic spikes — a sudden jump in network in means more requests hitting the server.</td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </div>

  <h2 class="mb-4 mt-10">CloudWatch alarms</h2>
  <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4">Set alarms that notify you before things break. These are your early warning system:</p>

  <div class="overflow-x-auto mb-6">
    <table class="w-full text-sm border-collapse">
      <thead>
        <tr class="bg-bg-muted">
          <th class="text-left px-4 py-3 font-semibold border-b border-border">Alarm</th>
          <th class="text-left px-4 py-3 font-semibold border-b border-border">Threshold</th>
          <th class="text-left px-4 py-3 font-semibold border-b border-border">Action</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr class="border-b border-border">
          <td class="px-4 py-3">CPU > 80% for 5 minutes</td>
          <td class="px-4 py-3 text-text-secondary">Sustained high CPU</td>
          <td class="px-4 py-3 text-text-secondary">Investigate immediately. Check for runaway processes or unexpected traffic.</td>
        </tr>
        <tr class="border-b border-border bg-bg-subtle">
          <td class="px-4 py-3">Memory > 85%</td>
          <td class="px-4 py-3 text-text-secondary">Running out of memory</td>
          <td class="px-4 py-3 text-text-secondary">Containers may start crashing. Check <code class="bg-bg-muted px-1.5 py-0.5 rounded text-xs font-mono">docker stats</code> for memory hogs.</td>
        </tr>
        <tr class="border-b border-border">
          <td class="px-4 py-3">Disk > 80%</td>
          <td class="px-4 py-3 text-text-secondary">Running out of disk</td>
          <td class="px-4 py-3 text-text-secondary">Clean up Docker images, rotate logs, or resize the volume.</td>
        </tr>
        <tr class="border-b border-border bg-bg-subtle">
          <td class="px-4 py-3">Status check failed</td>
          <td class="px-4 py-3 text-text-secondary">Instance unreachable</td>
          <td class="px-4 py-3 text-text-secondary">The instance is down. AWS sends this automatically. SSH in to diagnose or reboot.</td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </div>

  <Callout variant="info">
    <p class="text-sm"><strong>Configure alarm notifications via SNS.</strong> Create an SNS topic, subscribe your email address, and point the CloudWatch alarm at the topic. When CPU spikes or the instance goes down, you get an email. Without notifications, alarms fire silently — you'd only notice when Jake calls.</p>
  </Callout>

  <h2 class="mb-4 mt-10">CloudWatch Logs</h2>
  <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4">Ship application logs from Docker containers to CloudWatch Logs. Instead of SSHing into the instance and tailing log files every time something goes wrong, view them in the CloudWatch console.</p>
  <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4">Configure the CloudWatch agent to stream Docker container logs. The FastAPI backend produces the most useful logs — request logs, error logs, order events. Having these in CloudWatch means you can search and filter without SSH access.</p>

  <CodeBlock terminal copy>{`# On the EC2 instance: install and configure CloudWatch agent
$ sudo yum install -y amazon-cloudwatch-agent
$ sudo /opt/aws/amazon-cloudwatch-agent/bin/amazon-cloudwatch-agent-ctl \
    -a fetch-config -m ec2 -s

# Verify logs are flowing
# Go to CloudWatch > Log groups in the AWS console
# You should see log streams from your Docker containers`}</CodeBlock>

  <h2 class="mb-4 mt-10">Extension scenario: "Jake calls — the site is slow"</h2>
  <Callout variant="client">
    <p>"Hey, I've had three people today tell me the site is slow. One bloke said the tap list took ages to load on his phone. Can you take a look?"</p>
  </Callout>

  <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4">This is the scenario where monitoring pays off. Jake doesn't know what's wrong — he just knows customers are complaining. Your job is to diagnose using the tools you've set up.</p>

  <h3 class="mb-3 mt-6">Step 1: Check CloudWatch metrics</h3>
  <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4">Open the CloudWatch console. Look at the EC2 metrics for the last 24 hours:</p>
  <ul class="list-disc list-inside text-text-secondary space-y-2 text-sm mb-6">
    <li><strong class="text-text">CPU:</strong> Is it sustained above 80%? If so, the instance is at capacity.</li>
    <li><strong class="text-text">Memory:</strong> Is memory maxed out? Docker containers may be swapping to disk, which is extremely slow on a t2.micro.</li>
    <li><strong class="text-text">Disk:</strong> Is the disk full? A full disk causes everything to slow down or crash.</li>
    <li><strong class="text-text">Network:</strong> Is there a traffic spike? More requests than usual?</li>
  </ul>

  <h3 class="mb-3 mt-6">Step 2: Check application logs</h3>
  <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4">In CloudWatch Logs, look for:</p>
  <ul class="list-disc list-inside text-text-secondary space-y-2 text-sm mb-6">
    <li><strong class="text-text">Slow query warnings:</strong> Is a database query taking seconds instead of milliseconds?</li>
    <li><strong class="text-text">Error spikes:</strong> Are there more 500 errors than usual?</li>
    <li><strong class="text-text">Connection pool exhaustion:</strong> "Too many connections" errors mean the database can't handle the load.</li>
  </ul>

  <h3 class="mb-3 mt-6">Step 3: SSH in and check directly</h3>
  <CodeBlock terminal copy>{`# SSH into the instance
$ ssh -i ~/.ssh/your-key.pem ec2-user@<ec2-public-ip>

# Check container resource usage
$ docker stats --no-stream
# Shows CPU and memory for each container

# Check container logs for errors
$ docker logs tidal-backend --tail 50
$ docker logs tidal-db --tail 50

# Check disk space
$ df -h
# If / is above 80%, that's a problem`}</CodeBlock>

  <h3 class="mb-3 mt-6">Step 4: Identify and resolve</h3>
  <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4">Common root causes for a slow brewery site:</p>
  <ul class="list-disc list-inside text-text-secondary space-y-2 text-sm mb-6">
    <li><strong class="text-text">Docker logs filling disk:</strong> Containers produce logs. Without log rotation, they fill the disk. Add <code class="bg-bg-muted px-1.5 py-0.5 rounded text-xs font-mono">--log-opt max-size=10m --log-opt max-file=3</code> to your Docker Compose config.</li>
    <li><strong class="text-text">Memory pressure:</strong> PostgreSQL + FastAPI + React + Nginx on 1 GB RAM is tight. If memory is consistently above 85%, resize to t2.small (2 GB).</li>
    <li><strong class="text-text">Unoptimised images:</strong> Beer images served directly from the API instead of S3. Large images slow everything down. Serve them from S3 with proper caching headers.</li>
    <li><strong class="text-text">Missing database indexes:</strong> The tap list query is doing a full table scan. Add an index on the status column.</li>
  </ul>

  <Callout variant="warning">
    <p class="text-sm"><strong>Fix the root cause, not the symptom.</strong> Resizing the instance is easy — change the Terraform config and apply. But if the root cause is unrotated logs filling the disk, a bigger instance just delays the problem. Diagnose first, then fix the right thing.</p>
  </Callout>

  <h2 class="mb-4 mt-10">Production verification</h2>
  <ul class="text-sm text-text-secondary list-disc list-inside space-y-2 mb-8">
    <li>Tap list loads in under 2 seconds on mobile</li>
    <li>Events page shows upcoming events in date order</li>
    <li>Pickup ordering works end-to-end</li>
    <li>Admin interface is responsive and updates are instant</li>
    <li>CloudWatch alarms are configured and tested (trigger a test alarm)</li>
    <li>CloudWatch Logs show application logs from all containers</li>
    <li>HTTPS is active with auto-renewing certificate</li>
    <li>Beer images load from S3, not from the EC2 instance</li>
  </ul>

