  <h2 class="mb-4 mt-10">Reflect</h2>
  <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4">This was your first cloud deploy. Your first Terraform. Your first time managing your own infrastructure. That's a significant shift. Ask yourself:</p>
  <ul class="text-sm text-text-secondary list-disc list-inside space-y-2 mb-6">
    <li><strong class="text-text">PaaS vs IaaS:</strong> What did you gain by managing your own infrastructure? What did you lose? When would you choose Netlify/Railway over EC2/Terraform?</li>
    <li><strong class="text-text">Terraform plan review:</strong> How did reviewing <code class="bg-bg-muted px-1.5 py-0.5 rounded text-xs font-mono">terraform plan</code> compare to reviewing a code PR? What did you catch in the plan that would have been a problem?</li>
    <li><strong class="text-text">Infrastructure awareness:</strong> Before this project, you deployed to a platform and didn't think about the server. Now you know the instance size, the security group rules, the ports, the disk space. How does that change how you think about deployment?</li>
    <li><strong class="text-text">The monitoring question:</strong> When Jake called about the slow site, how did CloudWatch help you diagnose it? What would you have done without monitoring?</li>
    <li><strong class="text-text">Cost awareness:</strong> Did you stay within the free tier? Did the billing alert fire? How does infrastructure cost factor into architecture decisions?</li>
  </ul>

  <h2 class="mb-4 mt-10">The "show someone" moment</h2>
  <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4">Open the Tidal Brewing website on your phone. Show someone:</p>
  <ul class="text-sm text-text-secondary list-disc list-inside space-y-2 mb-6">
    <li>The tap list — live, fast, looks like a real Brunswick brewery's website</li>
    <li>The events page — upcoming trivia and live music at the taproom</li>
    <li>The pickup order form — simple, functional, only shows what's on tap</li>
    <li>Then open the AWS console — show the EC2 instance, the CloudWatch dashboard, the Terraform state</li>
  </ul>
  <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4">"I built the app and I built the infrastructure it runs on. Everything is defined in code — the server, the firewall rules, the monitoring. I can tear it down and rebuild it from a single command."</p>
  <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4">That last part — showing the Terraform configuration and saying "this creates everything" — is the proof that you understand infrastructure, not just applications.</p>

  <Callout variant="info">
    <p class="text-sm"><strong>Key insight:</strong> The shift from PaaS to IaaS isn't just a deployment change — it's a responsibility change. You're now accountable for uptime, security, cost, and performance at the infrastructure level. Terraform makes that manageable by treating infrastructure like code: version controlled, reviewable, reproducible.</p>
  </Callout>

  <details class="my-8 border border-border rounded-lg overflow-hidden">
    <summary class="px-6 py-4 bg-bg-muted cursor-pointer font-semibold text-sm">The landscape: cloud monitoring</summary>
    <div class="px-6 py-4">
      <p class="text-sm text-text-secondary mb-4">We use CloudWatch because we're on AWS. Here's what else exists for cloud monitoring.</p>
      <div class="space-y-3">
        <div>
          <p class="text-sm"><strong class="text-text">CloudWatch</strong> — <span class="text-text-secondary">What we use. AWS-native monitoring. Metrics, logs, alarms, dashboards. Free tier includes basic EC2 metrics. Tight integration with all AWS services. Vendor lock-in — only works with AWS.</span></p>
        </div>
        <div>
          <p class="text-sm"><strong class="text-text">Datadog</strong> — <span class="text-text-secondary">SaaS monitoring platform. Infrastructure metrics, application performance monitoring (APM), log management, and alerting in one tool. Works with any cloud provider. Expensive at scale but feature-rich. Popular in startups and mid-size companies.</span></p>
        </div>
        <div>
          <p class="text-sm"><strong class="text-text">New Relic</strong> — <span class="text-text-secondary">Full-stack observability platform. APM, infrastructure monitoring, log management, browser monitoring. Strong application-level visibility. Free tier is generous for small teams. Competes directly with Datadog.</span></p>
        </div>
        <div>
          <p class="text-sm"><strong class="text-text">Grafana Cloud</strong> — <span class="text-text-secondary">Hosted Grafana with Prometheus (metrics), Loki (logs), and Tempo (traces). Open-source foundations with a managed service layer. Popular with teams that want flexibility without vendor lock-in. Free tier available.</span></p>
        </div>
        <div>
          <p class="text-sm"><strong class="text-text">Prometheus + Grafana (self-hosted)</strong> — <span class="text-text-secondary">The open-source monitoring stack. Prometheus scrapes metrics, Grafana visualises them. No vendor lock-in, no per-host pricing. Operational overhead — you run and maintain the monitoring infrastructure yourself.</span></p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <p class="text-sm text-text-secondary mt-4">CloudWatch is the natural starting point on AWS — zero setup, basic metrics for free. When you need cross-cloud monitoring, deeper APM, or better dashboards, Datadog, New Relic, or Grafana Cloud are the common next steps.</p>
    </div>
  </details>

